{{Infobox software | name = Ametys CMS | title = | logo = Ametys CMS logo.png | logo size = 150px | screenshot = | caption = | collapsible = | developer = Ametys | status = Active | latest release version = 3.7.1 | latest release date = {{release date|2015|04|27}} | operating system = [[Cross-platform]] | size = | programming language = [[Java (programming language)|Java]] | genre = [[Content management system]], [[content management framework]] | license = [[Apache License]] 2.0 | website = {{url|http://www.ametys.org}} }} '''Ametys''' is a [[free and open source software|free and open source]] [[content management system]] (CMS) written in [[Java (programming language)|Java]]. It is based on [[Content repository API for Java|JSR-170]] for content storage,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dev.day.com/content/ddc/blog/2008/01/ametys.html|title=Ask the community and JCR|accessdate=|last=|first=|date=2008-01-16|work=Michael Marth|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100520114430/http://dev.day.com/content/ddc/blog/2008/01/ametys.html|archive-date=2010-05-20|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> [[OpenSocial|Open Social]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://docs.opensocial.org/display/OSREF/List+of+OpenSocial+Containers |title=List of OpenSocial Containers |accessdate= |last= |first= |date= |work=Jonathan LeBlanc}}</ref> for gadget rendering and a XML oriented framework. It is primarily designed to run large corporate websites, blogs, [[intranet]]s and [[extranet]]s on the same server.
{{As of|2012|05}}, Ametys claims to run more than 30 000 websites.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
Ametys is Java based <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ohloh.net/p/ametys/analyses/latest/languages_summary |title=Ametys Project on ohloh.net |accessdate= |last= |first= |date= |work=ohloh.net/}}</ref> and runs on any [[computing platform]] capable of running the [[Java Runtime Environment]] and an [[application server]].
== History == '''Ametys''' is a [[professional open-source]] CMS ([[content management system]]) written in Java.
Ametys was created in 2003 by Web and Java passionated experts and was then ported to the level of a professional open source CMS by Anyware Services (headquarters in [[France]]) in 2009.
Since 2005 and deployments of Ametys in higher education, specific components for [[uPortal]] and [[Jasig]] projects were developed.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} Ametys evolved through the collaboration of the community of developers, users and integrators.
The downloadable version includes user authentication via [[LDAP]] and [[Central Authentication Service|CAS]], and a [[WYSIWYG]] editor administration.
Ametys 3.4 was released in August 2012 and saw several improvements and new functionality including new plugins as [[User-generated content|UGC]], glossary, FAQ, and blog management. It also included new practices of [[Social web]].
== Modules == Ametys comes with many features : * Multi-site and multilingual platform * Front-end editing * [[RSS]] feed support * Document library manager, [[Alfresco (software)|Alfresco]] and other document library integration * [[LDAP]] Integration * Website Tools : comments feed, [[ShareThis|Share buttons]], Twitter feed integration, [[OpenSocial|OpenSocial gadgets]] * Blogs and wikis * Newsletter management * Web Form management * Online survey management * Maps
