{{Other uses|Dear John (disambiguation){{!}}Dear John}}
A '''Dear John letter''' is a letter written to a man by his wife or romantic partner to inform him their relationship is over because she has found another lover. The man is often a soldier stationed overseas, although the letter may be used in other ways, including being left for him to discover when he returns from work to an emptied house. Usually sent after time away on holiday
== Origin and etymology ==
While the exact origins of the phrase are unknown, it is commonly believed to have been coined by Americans during [[World War II]]. "John" was the most popular and common baby name for boys in America every single year from 1880 through 1923,<ref>https://www.ssa.gov/OACT/babynames/index.html</ref> making it a reasonable 'placeholder' name when denoting those of age for military service. Large numbers of [[American troops]] were stationed overseas for many months or years, and as time passed many of their wives or girlfriends decided to begin a relationship with a new man rather than to wait for the original one to return.{{Citation needed|date = March 2017}}
As letters to servicemen from wives or girlfriends back home would typically contain affectionate language (such as "Dear Johnny", "My dearest John", or simply "Darling"), a serviceman receiving a note beginning with a curt "Dear John" would instantly be aware of the letter's purpose.{{Citation needed|date = March 2017}}
A writer in the ''[[Democrat and Chronicle]]'' of [[Rochester, New York]], summed it up in August 1945:
{{quote|"Dear John," the letter began. "I have found someone else whom I think the world of. I think the only way out is for us to get a [[Divorce in the United States|divorce]]," it said. They usually began like that, those letters that told of infidelity on the part of the wives of servicemen... The men called them "Dear Johns".<ref name="auto">{{cite web|last=Quinion|first=Michael|title=Dear John letter|url=http://www.worldwidewords.org/qa/qa-dea5.htm|work=World Wide Words|accessdate=7 January 2014|date=13 Dec 2003}}</ref> }}
An early reference to Dear John letters was made in a [[United Press]] article of March 21, 1944.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=j9M0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=oE4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=7082,6366557&dq=dear-john-letter&hl=en Hollywood Girls Gain Weight on Tour of Africa] [[St. Petersburg Times]], March 21, 1944.</ref> It has been claimed that the [[Vietnam War]] inspired more Dear John letters than any other US conflict.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gross|first=Chuck|title=Rattler One-Seven: A Vietnam Helicopter Pilot's War Story|year=2006|publisher=University of North Texas Press|page=173|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xFvbGYGdn_gC&lpg=PA173&dq=Dear%20John%20letter&pg=PA173#v=onepage&q=Dear%20John%20letter&f=false}}</ref> Later, this type of letter formed background to the British television show ''[[Dear John (UK TV series)|Dear John]]'', and the [[Dear John (U.S. TV series)|American sitcom of the same name]].{{Citation needed|date = March 2017}} A ''Dear Jane'' letter is a contemporary version of a ''Dear John'' letter addressed to a female lover.<ref name="auto"/>
== Employment ==
This term is also used to describe letters written in the context of employment, either to inform an applicant that they had not been selected for a job,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://humanresources.about.com/b/2011/10/26/say-no-thanks-with-care.htm|title=Communicating with Candidates for Your Job|author=Susan M. Heathfield|work=About.com Money}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrcommunication.com/Main/Articles/The_Dear_John_letter_to_candidates_Follow_this_pro_8694.aspx|title=The ‘Dear John’ letter to candidates: Follow this protocol|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://howtowritewhatever.com/how-to-write-a-dear-john-letter|title=How to write a "Dear John" letter|publisher=}}</ref> why employees had been separated from work,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wonkette.com/530241/obama-sends-dear-john-letter-to-federal-workers-its-not-you-its-congress|title=Obama Sends ‘Dear John’ Letter To Federal Workers: It’s Not You, It’s Congress|author=DDM|date=1 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref> or from an employee to their employer upon the employee quitting.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/former_denr_employee_leaves_her_job_with_a_blazing_dear_john_email |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102204934/http://projects.newsobserver.com/under_the_dome/former_denr_employee_leaves_her_job_with_a_blazing_dear_john_email |archivedate=2014-01-02 |df= }}</ref>
